The aetiological agent, SARS CoV, was identified within weeks of global spread [11], [12], [13] and this discovery was followed by an impressive sequence of research accomplishments. These included the development of diagnostic assays; the characterisation of the clinical, epidemiological and virological features of infection [14]; the identification and initial evaluation of antiviral drugs (Table 1
) [15], [16], [17]; the development of animal models of SARS CoV infection [18], [19], [20], [21], [22]; the development and evaluation of candidate vaccines (Table 2
) [23], [24], [25], [26]; the identification of receptors for SARS CoV [27], [28]; the development of a reverse genetics system [29] and more. From the discovery of the virus in March 2003, until October 2009, there have been ∼3000 articles published on the virus, the clinical and epidemiological features of infection, the social and societal impact of the outbreak and the treatment and prevention of the disease.
